# Partition, test and train -----------------------------------------------
set.seed(0)

#split clean data into train and test so I can start training models
#This will create an 80/20 split of randomly selected row numbers with 80% train 20% test
bank.Index<-createDataPartition(y=bankdata$y, 
                                p = .8,list = FALSE,times = 1)

# assign the test and train rows to their own data sets
bankTrain<-bankdata[bank.Index,]
bankTest<-bankdata[-bank.Index,]

#Sanity check to verify data has been split 80/20

# Model Selection ----------------------------------------------------------------


# create null and full models (intact park code)
model.null = glm(y ~ 1, 
                 data = bankTrain,
                 family = binomial) # null model : no predictor
model.full = m1

# stepwise selection with BIC
step.models.BIC<-step(model.null, scope = list(upper=model.full),
                      direction="both",test="Chisq", trace = F, k=log(nrow(bankTrain)))

# stepwise selection with AIC
step.models.AIC<-step(model.null, scope = list(upper=model.full),
                      direction="both",test="Chisq", trace = F) 


summary(step.models.BIC)   # summary of stepwise selection with BIC

# RF MODEL for comparison

#Create cross-validation control for the predictive models
# This will tell it to use crossvalidation with 3 repeats
modelControl <- trainControl(method = "repeatedcv", repeats = 3)
#Random Forest model
set.seed(0)

RF  <- train(y ~ .- poutcome, 
             method="rf", trControl=modelControl, data=bankTrain, verbose=FALSE)
#GBM model
set.seed(0)

GBM <- train(y ~ .- poutcome, 
             method='gbm', trControl=modelControl, data=bankTrain, verbose=FALSE)
#SVM model
set.seed(0)

SVM <- train(y ~ .- poutcome, 
             method="svmLinear", trControl=modelControl, data=bankTrain, verbose=FALSE)

GBM_matrix <- caret::confusionMatrix(bankTest$pred_GBM, as.factor(bankTest$y), positive = "yes")
SVM_matrix <-caret::confusionMatrix(bankTest$pred_SVM, as.factor(bankTest$y), positive = "yes")

Model <- c("RF", "GBM", "SVM")
Accuracy <- c(RF_matrix$overall[1], GBM_matrix$overall[1], SVM_matrix$overall[1])
Sensitivity <- c(RF_matrix$byClass[1], GBM_matrix$byClass[1], SVM_matrix$byClass[1])
Specificity <- c(RF_matrix$byClass[2], GBM_matrix$byClass[2], SVM_matrix$byClass[2])
data.frame(Model, Accuracy, Sensitivity, Specificity)
##   Model  Accuracy Sensitivity Specificity
## 1    RF 0.8927681  0.03409091   0.9985994
## 2   GBM 0.9002494  0.19318182   0.9873950
## 3   SVM 0.8877805  0.11363636   0.9831933

GBM has the best balance of all three measures, and is faster to train
